Plus Bank Churn Analysis

ğŸ“Œ Project Overview

This project analyzes customer churn for Plus Bank, using data from 1,000 customers across France, Germany, and Spain.
The aim is to identify the major drivers of churn and provide insights for improving customer retention.


---

ğŸ“Š Dataset Summary

Total customers analyzed: 1,000

Customers currently still banking with Plus Bank: 7,962 (overall bank-wide number)

Average customer age: 39 years

Regions covered: France, Germany, Spain



---

ğŸ” Key Findings

1. Demographics

Majority of customers who churned were female.

Most belonged to the Gen X age group (40â€“55 years).


2. Account Information

Churned customers had accounts for 8 to 10 years.

Many held a medium account balance.

Their credit scores were generally average to good â€” meaning creditworthiness was not a major churn driver.


3. Product & Activity Insights

Most churned customers owned more than 2 products.

Many had credit cards.

A significant portion were inactive members, indicating low engagement.

Churned customers also had higher complaint frequency, signaling dissatisfaction.



---

ğŸŒ Country Insights

Plus Bank operates in France, Germany, and Spain.
Churn patterns were similar across all three countries, although specific rates may vary.


